{"id":"mai-kqnz","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Oracle 1: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian","tags":["research","oracle"],"body":"# Oracle 1: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian\n\n## 1. Instructor Framing Assessment\n\nMostly right, but two parts of the framing were misleading:\n\n- **The core symptom description is accurate.** The current sync path can absolutely explode document size with repeated duplicated fragments after external file edits.\n- **`lastSyncBody()` is a red herring in the current code.** It has a TODO and returns `\"\"`, but it is also **unused**. The live code path does not call it. The actual merge base comes from `creation.Body` passed into `mergeViaCRDT(...)` from `SyncDocs`.\n- **`mai ls --tag research` / `mai ls --tag plan` is not a valid CLI today.** I verified from `mai ls` help that `--tag` does not exist. I had to find prior research/plan material manually from `mai ls`, `mai closed`, and `mai show`.\n- **Atomic saves matter for daemon delete/tombstone behavior, but they are not required to trigger the body corruption bug.** I reproduced the duplication with plain in-place full-file rewrites and no rename/temp-file dance.\n\nBottom line: the framing pointed at the right area (`mergeViaCRDT` + Obsidian full saves), but the deepest bug is **stale merge ancestry**, not `lastSyncBody()` itself.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Initial Hypotheses (from PRIMARY evidence)\n\nAfter reading the code and history, my initial hypotheses were:\n\n1. **The merge base is far too old.** Using creation-time body as the base for every later file save will replay the entire document history as if it were a fresh concurrent edit each time.\n2. **Obsidian's full-file autosave will amplify that mistake.** If the editor writes the whole file every time, then diffing `creationBody -\u003e currentFile` re-sends all older insertions on every save.\n3. **The bug is probably not in yrs itself.** The CRDT tests show that when two docs actually share history and merge via full state, convergence works.\n4. **The current test suite is missing the real-world save pattern.** Existing docs tests mostly cover one edit or rapid edits with immediate sync, but not repeated full-file rewrites from a moving external editor baseline.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Research Path — every avenue explored\n\n### Mandatory code review completed\nI read these files completely:\n\n- `pkg/crdt/crdt.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/diff.go`\n- `pkg/notes/docs.go`\n- `cmd/mai/daemon.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/crdt_test.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/diff_test.go`\n- `test/docs_daemon_fsnotify_test.go`\n- `test/docs_daemon_test.go`\n- `test/docs_adversarial_test.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/yrs-wasi/src/lib.rs`\n\nI also read the relevant `pkg/notes` boundary note from `pkg/notes/AGENTS.md`.\n\n### Related code I had to inspect to understand wiring\n- `pkg/notes/engine.go` — `Append`, `initYDoc`, `updateYDoc`, `autoSyncDoc`, `prevNoteBody`\n- `pkg/notes/fold.go` — how `field=ydoc` is folded\n- `pkg/notes/types.go` — `State.YDocState`\n- `test/docs_test.go`\n- `test/obsidian_compat_test.sh`\n\n### Prior tickets / plans / artifacts reviewed\nSince `mai ls --tag` is unavailable, I manually reviewed:\n\n- `mai-4z3y` — Delphi epic\n- `mai-n5q3` — CRDT docs layer architecture ticket\n- `mai-prg8` — prior Obsidian + CRDT duplication bug report\n- `mai-k1gv` — CRDT wiring plan\n- `mai-gnho` — session handoff\n- `mai-diso` — duplicate target/path collision fix\n- `mai-yi0r` — follow-up commit ticket\n\n### Git history reviewed\nI checked the full path history for `pkg/crdt/`, `pkg/notes/docs.go`, and `cmd/mai/daemon.go`, then inspected the important commits:\n\n- `8ea1ad8` — initial CRDT text engine\n- `1aae181` — unique client IDs + full-state merge fix\n- `4ecfad6` — diff engine\n- `d6c9944` — CRDT 3-way merge added to `SyncDocs`\n- `32d370a` — frontmatter preservation\n- `9c6e6bb` — daemon delete debounce for atomic saves\n\n### Web / external research\nI checked:\n\n- Obsidian autosave behavior\n- Yjs/Y.Doc update/state-vector semantics\n- Known duplication failure mode when external systems overwrite full text instead of applying precise changes\n- How other markdown note tools approach file sync\n\nKey external sources:\n\n- `obsidian-autosave-control` README: **Obsidian saves every ~2 seconds while you type** by default.\n- Yjs update docs: state vectors and update diffs are about **missing changes relative to known CRDT state**, not recreating peers from raw text snapshots.\n- StackOverflow / Yjs duplication answer: if concurrent peers effectively overwrite whole content instead of applying precise changes, **Yjs keeps both insertions**, causing duplication.\n- Dendron / Foam docs: both are fundamentally **plain markdown file systems**, not CRDT-backed external sync.\n- Logseq docs/community: also markdown-first on disk historically; the file format story is about markdown portability, not CRDT-merging external full-file saves.\n\n### Reproduction work I ran myself\n#### A. Pure-CRDT reproduction of the current algorithm\nI recreated the logic of `mergeViaCRDT` in a temp Go program.\n\nMinimal reproduction:\n\n- base = `\"A\"`\n- note = `\"AB\"`\n- file = `\"ABC\"`\n- merged result = `\"ABCB\"`\n\nAnother:\n\n- base = `\"Hello\"`\n- note = `\"Hello brave new\"`\n- file = `\"Hello brave new world\"`\n- merged result = `\"Hello brave new world brave new\"`\n\nThis proves the algorithm duplicates old insertions when the file save is based on a later snapshot than the chosen base.\n\n#### B. End-to-end `SyncDocs` reproduction in a temp repo\nI created a temp git repo, made one doc note with body `\"if one day we\"`, materialized it, then repeatedly simulated Obsidian-style **full-file rewrites** by appending a tiny change and calling `notes.SyncDocs(...)`.\n\nObserved growth of `\"can merge\"` occurrences in the note body:\n\n- round 1: 1\n- round 2: 2\n- round 3: 4\n- round 4: 8\n- round 5: 16\n- round 6: 32\n\nThe body length grew from 25 → 46 → 90 → 179 → 352 → 694.\n\nThat is the bug. It is not subtle. It is an exponential replay of old text.\n\n#### C. Current tests still pass\nI ran focused existing tests:\n\n- `TestDocsSync_FileEditUpdatesNote`\n- `TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged`\n- `TestDocs_RapidEditsAllPersist`\n\nThey all pass. So the current suite does **not** catch the real Obsidian failure mode.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Dead Ends and why they were dead ends\n\n### Dead end 1: `lastSyncBody()` as the root cause\nIt looked suspicious because it is unfinished, but it is not used anywhere. Fixing only that function would change nothing until the call site changes.\n\n### Dead end 2: blaming yrs / client IDs / full-state merge\nThat was an older bug, but the history shows it was already fixed in `1aae181` with unique client IDs and full-state merge. The current duplication is happening **above** yrs, in how maitake fabricates ancestry for file edits.\n\n### Dead end 3: atomic save behavior as the main explanation\nThe daemon does care about atomic save patterns (`Remove` + `Create`) so it does not tombstone live notes. But the duplication bug reproduces with a plain `os.WriteFile` full rewrite. So atomic save is relevant to watcher correctness, not merge correctness.\n\n### Dead end 4: assuming the problem is only \"both note and file changed\"\nIt is worse than that. The corruption can happen on repeated **file-side-only** edits if each file edit is merged against the original creation body instead of the last synced state.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Key Discoveries with evidence\n\n### Discovery 1: `mergeViaCRDT` uses the creation body as merge base\nIn `SyncDocs`, when note and disk differ, the code fetches `engine.Get(id)` and passes `creation.Body` into `mergeViaCRDT(...)`.\n\nThat means every later file save is treated as a diff from the document's birth, not from the most recent sync point.\n\n### Discovery 2: `lastSyncBody()` is dead code\nThere is a TODO function with the right name, but nothing calls it. The live path ignores it entirely.\n\n### Discovery 3: the current CRDT merge is not using real shared ancestry for the file peer\n`mergeViaCRDT` does this:\n\n1. load current note YDoc state\n2. read `noteContent`\n3. create a **fresh** base doc from `creationBody`\n4. create a note peer from that base using `Diff(base, noteContent)`\n5. create a file peer from that base using `Diff(base, fileContent)`\n6. merge full state\n\nThis only works if `base` is the actual common ancestor of both snapshots. With Obsidian-style repeated full rewrites, it is not.\n\n### Discovery 4: repeated full-file saves produce exponential duplication\nMy end-to-end reproduction showed exact doubling of a repeated fragment each sync: 2, 4, 8, 16, 32.\n\nThis matches the reported real-world symptom: the content does not merely drift; it **explodes**.\n\n### Discovery 5: yrs itself is behaving consistently\nThe CRDT tests in `pkg/crdt/crdt_test.go` pass because they use docs that actually share CRDT history. So the underlying library is not the thing inventing garbage here.\n\n### Discovery 6: `SyncDocs` emits two ydoc updates on file import/update paths\nWhen `SyncDocs` does `engine.Append(... field=\"body\" ...)`, `Append()` itself calls `updateYDoc(...)` for doc notes.\nThen `SyncDocs` may append another explicit `field=\"ydoc\"` event with `merged.YDocState`.\n\nSo a file-driven merge path can create:\n\n- one body event\n- one ydoc event from `updateYDoc`\n- one extra ydoc event from `SyncDocs`\n\nThat is not the primary corruption bug, but it is a sign the design has two competing sources of truth for YDoc updates.\n\n### Discovery 7: current tests cover one-shot edits, not Obsidian's steady-state behavior\nThe tests check:\n\n- note → file\n- file → note\n- one conflict case\n- rapid edits with immediate syncs\n- daemon atomic-save tombstone protection\n\nThey do **not** check the critical invariant:\n\n\u003e repeated full-file saves from the current on-disk body must not reintroduce already-synced text\n\n### Discovery 8: Obsidian really does autosave frequently\nThe external evidence is consistent that default Obsidian behavior is autosave roughly every 2 seconds while typing. That means the broken merge path is exercised repeatedly in normal use.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Contradicting Evidence\n\nI looked for evidence against the obvious story, and found some important qualifiers:\n\n- **The exact repeated fragment varies.** In the user symptom it was `\"if one day we\"`. In my reproduction the doubled fragment was later text like `\"can merge\"`. So the repeated slice depends on diff chunk boundaries, not a single magic phrase.\n- **The CRDT package is not generally broken.** Shared-history full-state merges converge in tests.\n- **Atomic saves are not necessary for the duplication.** So if anyone insists \"this must be an fsnotify bug\", that is contradicted by direct reproduction.\n- **A doc can corrupt even without concurrent human+agent edits.** Repeated editor saves alone are enough if ancestry is stale.\n- **Today maitake does not yet have a true end-to-end multi-peer CRDT note merge.** `field=ydoc` is still folded last-writer-wins. That means CRDT is being used locally inside sync logic, but the broader replicated-note design is incomplete.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Synthesis — my answer\n\n## Short answer\n\n**Do not use the current CRDT reconstruction strategy for Obsidian sync.**\nFor Obsidian and other full-file-save editors, the correct merge model is:\n\n1. **Track an explicit last-synced base snapshot** for each doc\n2. Compare three snapshots on sync:\n   - `base` = what was last materialized to disk\n   - `note` = current note body\n   - `file` = current file body\n3. Handle cases deterministically:\n   - `note == file` → no-op\n   - `note == base \u0026\u0026 file != base` → file-only change, import file\n   - `file == base \u0026\u0026 note != base` → note-only change, write note\n   - both changed from base → run a real **3-way text merge** on snapshots\n4. If the 3-way merge has **overlapping edits**, surface a conflict and do **not** silently rewrite the file\n5. After any successful sync, persist the new merged snapshot as the next `base`\n\nThat is the correct design for snapshot-based external editors.\n\n## Do we need CRDT here?\n\n**Not for this problem, not today.**\n\nFor local disk sync with Obsidian, the editor is not giving maitake CRDT operations. It is giving maitake whole-file snapshots. Once that is true, you already have a classic 3-way merge problem. A normal diff3/patience merge with a tracked sync base is simpler, easier to reason about, easier to test, and directly aligned with the data you actually have.\n\nThe current CRDT path is trying to reverse-engineer operations from snapshots and then pretend those snapshots are concurrent peers from the creation state. That is exactly why it corrupts documents.\n\n## When CRDT would make sense\n\nCRDT becomes worth it if maitake later implements a **real replicated text model end-to-end**, meaning:\n\n- note-side edits preserve CRDT ancestry across replicas\n- last synced **YDoc state** is tracked, not just creation body\n- remote ydoc updates are merged as CRDT updates, not folded last-writer-wins\n- file-side edits are converted relative to the **last synced YDoc snapshot**, not to the creation text\n\nIf you want to keep CRDT, the minimum correct design is:\n\n- store `last_sync_ydoc` (or equivalent) every time a file is materialized\n- build the file peer from **that** YDoc state\n- merge file peer into the current note doc, which actually descends from that state\n- update `last_sync_ydoc` after success\n\nWithout that ancestor snapshot, the CRDT merge is fake.\n\n## My recommendation\n\n### Recommended now: snapshot-based 3-way merge, no CRDT in `SyncDocs`\nThis is the highest-payoff fix for Obsidian compatibility.\n\nWhy I recommend it:\n\n- matches actual external editor behavior\n- solves the corruption bug directly\n- easier to verify and keep correct\n- avoids duplicating huge YDoc blobs just to track file ancestry\n- does not block future CRDT work if you later want repo-to-repo collaborative text merge\n\n### If you insist on CRDT now\nThen the contract must change:\n\n- stop using `creationBody` as ancestor\n- persist `last_sync_ydoc`\n- stop emitting duplicate ydoc events from both `Append(body)` and `SyncDocs`\n- implement real ydoc merge semantics for concurrent note replicas, not just local sync\n\nThat is a much larger project than the current bug fix.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Concrete testing strategy\n\n## A. Unit tests for merge logic (pure function tests)\nCreate a merge helper that takes `base`, `note`, `file` and returns either merged body or conflict.\n\nRequired cases:\n\n1. `base == note == file` → no-op\n2. file-only change\n3. note-only change\n4. non-overlapping concurrent edits\n5. overlapping concurrent edits → conflict\n6. repeated full-file rewrites from evolving file state → **must not duplicate prior text**\n7. large markdown with headings, lists, code fences, YAML-like body text\n8. unicode / emoji / CJK\n\nCritical regression test:\n\n- base: `if one day we`\n- then simulate repeated file rewrites appending one small fragment per round\n- assert the repeated token count stays **1**, not 2/4/8/16/32\n\nIf CRDT is kept, add a second unit suite:\n\n- `last_sync_ydoc` as common ancestor\n- repeated file rewrites do not duplicate\n- no use of creation body beyond initial materialization\n\n## B. Integration tests simulating Obsidian save behavior\nAdd tests around `notes.SyncDocs(...)` that do full-file rewrites of the materialized markdown file, not incremental line edits.\n\nRequired integration cases:\n\n1. create doc → materialize → rewrite full file → sync → note matches file exactly\n2. repeat that save/sync cycle 5-10 times → note still matches file exactly\n3. note edit + full-file save from old base → auto-merge non-overlapping changes\n4. overlapping note/file edits → conflict surfaced, file left untouched\n5. restart engine after sync → persisted state still correct\n6. large doc (~2700 words) with small external edit → no duplication explosion\n7. frontmatter preserved through every cycle\n\n## C. Daemon / fsnotify tests\nUse daemon-style tests for watcher behavior separately from merge behavior.\n\nRequired cases:\n\n1. plain write events\n2. atomic save (`Remove` + quick `Create`)\n3. autosave burst (many writes in short window)\n4. edit after `rm -rf docs/` and restore\n5. repeated Obsidian-style saves do not tombstone and do not corrupt body\n\n## D. Adversarial / property-style tests\nThis problem is ideal for invariants:\n\n### Invariants to check\n- syncing twice with no changes is a no-op\n- after successful sync, `file == note` in content\n- repeated file-only saves do not introduce new copies of old substrings\n- body length should grow roughly with actual edits, not exponentially\n- if merge reports conflict, file content remains unchanged\n\n### Suggested randomized test\nGenerate:\n\n- random markdown-ish base text\n- random sequence of file-only append/replace edits\n- optional interleaved note edits from the tracked base\n\nThen assert:\n\n- exact equality after one-sided changes\n- stable size bounds after repeated saves\n- no duplicated sentinel fragments\n\n---\n\n## 9. Confidence \u0026 Caveats\n\n## Confidence: High on root cause\nI directly reproduced the corruption both:\n\n- in a pure reconstruction of `mergeViaCRDT`\n- through `notes.SyncDocs(...)` in a temp repo\n\nThe doubling pattern is too clean to be incidental.\n\n## Confidence: Medium on exact Obsidian write mechanics\nI have strong evidence that Obsidian autosaves frequently (~2s while typing). I did not instrument live Obsidian filesystem calls in this session, so I am less certain about whether every platform/build uses rename-based atomic save or plain overwrite for every save.\n\nThat caveat does **not** weaken the root-cause conclusion, because the corruption reproduces without atomic saves.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Divergent Possibilities\n\n### Path A — Recommended\n**Replace `mergeViaCRDT` in `SyncDocs` with snapshot-based diff3 using tracked last-sync base.**\n\nPros:\n- directly solves the bug\n- simpler and safer\n- easier tests\n- aligned with Obsidian reality\n\nCons:\n- CRDT package becomes unused in file sync for now\n\n### Path B — Larger, CRDT-pure route\n**Keep CRDT, but add `last_sync_ydoc` and real ancestor-aware merge.**\n\nPros:\n- keeps long-term CRDT story alive\n- could support future multi-replica text merging better\n\nCons:\n- much more state to store and reason about\n- current note-folding model still needs deeper work for true replicated ydoc merge\n\n### Path C — Simpler but lower payoff\n**Track last-sync base and use last-write-wins on overlap.**\n\nPros:\n- very easy to ship\n- still fixes duplication\n\nCons:\n- loses one side's overlapping edits\n- weaker user story than real diff3 conflict handling\n\n## Final recommendation\n\nShip **Path A now**.\n\nUse a tracked sync base + text 3-way merge for disk sync. Keep CRDT out of `SyncDocs` until maitake is ready to track real YDoc ancestry across sync points and across replicas.","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:23:45Z","branch":"main"}

